</li>\r\n	<li>Exposure Triangle and Stops</li>\r\n	<li>When to use what</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Focus</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Auto Modes</li>\r\n	<li>Manual - When and How</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Misc</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>How to hold a camera</li>\r\n	<li>Recommended Gear</li>\r\n</ul>','101-Intro','Welcome to our 52Frames 101 Beginner’s guide!!','trash','open','open','','blog101-intro','','','2014-12-31 18:23:24','2014-12-31 18:23:24','',0,'http://52frames.com/?p=348',0,'post','',0),(349,4,'2014-12-28 00:18:11','2014-12-28 00:18:11','<h1>Welcome to our 52Frames 101 Beginner’s guide!!</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>This is the very first page of the rest of your life! OK, that doesn\'t make any sense, but if you take care to read through this guide, we promise that you will be on your way to understanding the foundations of photography, so that you can take ownership of scary terms like Av and ISO, and go on and just have fun with your new craft!</h2>\r\n<h2>In this guide, we have put together what we feel are the most important subjects a photographer needs to learn after unboxing their fancy shmancy camera.. We then culled the interwebs and gleaned the best, most concise tutorials for your knowledge receptors. If we couldn’t find something suitable, we made it ourselves.</h2>\r\n<h2>We’re proud to present this simple, concise program, to every budding photog that comes through our door. So get educated, and get going.</h2>\r\n<h2>What are you waiting for? Start HERE.</h2>\r\n<h2>[Table of Contents]\r\nHave “Coming Soon” for the ones that aren’t live yet</h2>','101-Intro','','inherit','open','open','','348-revision-v1','','','2014-12-28 00:18:11','2014-12-28 00:18:11','',348,'http://52frames.com/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(350,4,'2014-12-28 00:44:51','2014-12-28 00:44:51','<h1>Welcome to our 52Frames 101 Beginner’s guide!!</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>This is the very first page of the rest of your life! OK, that doesn\'t make any sense, but if you take care to read through this guide, we promise that you will be on your way to understanding the foundations of photography, so that you can take ownership of scary terms like Av and ISO, and go on and just have fun with your new craft!</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>In this guide, we have put together what we feel are the most important subjects a photographer needs to learn after unboxing their fancy shmancy camera.. We then culled the interwebs and gleaned the best, most concise tutorials for your knowledge receptors. If we couldn’t find something suitable, we made it ourselves.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>We’re proud to present this simple, concise program, to every budding photog that comes through our door. So get educated, and get going.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>What are you waiting for? Start HERE.</h2>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\nComposition\r\n\r\nRule of Thirds\r\n\r\nBalance\r\n\r\nLead in Lines\r\n\r\nComposition:Beyond the Rule of Thirds\r\n\r\nLooking into the frame\r\n\r\nMore dramatic composition\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExposure\r\n\r\nAuto with Exposure Compensation\r\n\r\nMetering Modes\r\n\r\nShutter Speed (and Tv)\r\n\r\nAperture (and Av)\r\n\r\nISO\r\n\r\nExposure Triangle and Stops\r\n\r\nWhen to use what\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFocus\r\n\r\nAuto Modes\r\n\r\nManual - When and How\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMisc\r\n\r\nHow to hold a camera\r\n\r\nRecommended Gear','101-Intro','','inherit','open','open','','348-revision-v1','','','2014-12-28 00:44:51','2014-12-28 00:44:51','',348,'http://52frames.com/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(351,4,'2014-12-28 15:32:55','2014-12-28 15:32:55','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.\r\n\r\nBy faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation we\'ve found online, comes from \'Web Video Crew\' in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU?rel=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nOne thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the <strong>intersecting</strong> points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into \'thirds\'. Although this is also a compositional technique with regards to <strong>balance</strong>, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.\r\n\r\nAnother great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the right side of the frame and facing left, as is the truck. The composition is such that there’s “room” for the surfer to surf ‘into’, or the truck to drive ‘into’. Pay mind to where your subject is “looking” and give space in the frame accordingly.\r\n\r\nAs with all our rules we dole out here at 52Frames, understand that many times they are meant to be broken, so don’t worry about getting it exact, just keep this in your \'toolbelt\' and keep it in mind when you shoot.\r\n\r\nNEXT UP: Balance','Rule of Thirds - The Most Important Rule You\'ll Ever Learn. (not really)','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.','publish','open','open','','rule-of-thirds-the-most-important-rule-youll-ever-learn-not-really','','','2014-12-31 20:30:26','2014-12-31 20:30:26','',0,'http://52frames.com/?p=351',0,'post','',0),(352,4,'2014-12-28 09:11:13','2014-12-28 09:11:13','<h1>The Rule of Thirds</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>By faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation I\'ve found online, comes from Web Video Crew in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>One thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the intersecting points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into 1/3rds. Although this is also a compositional technique, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Another great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the right side of the frame and facing left, as is the truck. The composition is such that there’s “room” for the surfer to surf ‘into’, or the truck to drive ‘into’. Pay mind to where your subject is “looking” and give space in the frame accordingly.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Don’t worry about getting it exact, just keep this in mind as you shoot.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>NEXT UP: Balance</h2>','101 - Rule of Thirds','','inherit','open','open','','351-revision-v1','','','2014-12-28 09:11:13','2014-12-28 09:11:13','',351,'http://52frames.com/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(353,4,'2014-12-28 09:11:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2014-12-28 09:11:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52frames.com/?p=353',0,'post','',0),(354,4,'2014-12-28 09:11:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2014-12-28 09:11:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52frames.com/?p=354',0,'post','',0),(355,4,'2014-12-28 09:12:44','2014-12-28 09:12:44','<h1>The Rule of Thirds</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>By faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation I\'ve found online, comes from Web Video Crew in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:</h2>\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU\" width=\"563\" height=\"563\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n<h2>One thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the intersecting points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into 1/3rds. Although this is also a compositional technique, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Another great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the right side of the frame and facing left, as is the truck. The composition is such that there’s “room” for the surfer to surf ‘into’, or the truck to drive ‘into’. Pay mind to where your subject is “looking” and give space in the frame accordingly.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Don’t worry about getting it exact, just keep this in mind as you shoot.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>NEXT UP: Balance</h2>','101 - Rule of Thirds','','inherit','open','open','','351-revision-v1','','','2014-12-28 09:12:44','2014-12-28 09:12:44','',351,'http://52frames.com/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(356,4,'2014-12-28 09:13:57','2014-12-28 09:13:57','<h1>The Rule of Thirds</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>By faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation I\'ve found online, comes from Web Video Crew in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:</h2>\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU\" width=\"563\" height=\"187\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n<h2>One thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the intersecting points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into 1/3rds. Although this is also a compositional technique, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Another great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the righ