 the week’s challenge. Sometimes we see a fantastic photo that feels like a “shoe-horn” (that’s what we call a photo that doesn’t reeeeally fit the theme), which is ok as a submission, but not for an award.\r\n\r\nArt is necessarily a subjective experience, so we try to assemble a panel of judges with different styles, tastes and preferences. Some of the most spirited arguments we’ve ever had were focused on which photograph should “win” a challenge. But we’re still friends.[/vc_toggle][/vc_tab][vc_tab title=\"The Rules\" tab_id=\"1419783734-2-51\"][vc_toggle title=\"I sure would love to see a page of the community guidelines, and rules. Where can I find such a thing?\" open=\"false\"]That wasn’t at all a contrived question that we had our fictional questioner pose! In fact, we do have such a page. <a title=\"Community Guidelines\" href=\"http://52frames.com/members/community-guidelines/\">Over here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"I have a great photo in my archive that’s PERFECT for this week. Can I submit it?\" open=\"false\"]No. You may ONLY submit a photo that was taken taken during the week of the present challenge. You are, however, welcome to share your photo goodnesses in our <a href=\"facebook.com/groups/52fadmin/\" target=\"_blank\">52Frames Photographers’ Facebook group</a> to inspire the community.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"Can I submit a photo that was shot just a few hours before last week’s deadline?\" open=\"false\"]No. The 52Frames project is a 7-day challenge, so push yourself to get one really creative and inventive shot, each week. The clock starts at 12:01pm, each Sunday, Eastern U.S. time, and ends at noon, the following week.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"Can I change my photo (or photo details) once I’ve submitted?\" open=\"false\"]Yes. (See? It’s not all “no”s).  Simply go to your photo page, and replace your photo with the new one. You’ll also be able to edit any information you put in for that photo.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"When is the deadline for the weekly challenge?\" open=\"false\"]The deadline each week is noon (12:00pm) Eastern U.S. time. (When in doubt, just google: “What time is it in New York”). We’ll wave our hands wildly in the air when we know about the clock being changed in different countries, but your best bet is simply not to wait until the last minute.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"If I miss a week, am I allowed to continue the project?\" open=\"false\"]Yes! But you will no longer be considered a “Weekly Warrior” (name pending), and you won’t be eligible for any badges or contests associated with it. While a successful 52-week run is ideal, we understand that life sometimes gets in the way, and it’s more important to just have fun, and post when you can! We believe consistency is the most important thing, so go ahead and submit a photo even if you’re not crazy about it! We’ll understand. (Also, some of the best shots we’ve seen were submitted by completely unenthusiastic members just trying to stay “consistent”).\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"Can I submit a photo after the deadline?\" open=\"false\"]No. The deadline is a HARD deadline, like a turtle shell, or umm, a very stale piece of bread. Any submission sent in after Sunday at noon Eastern U.S., will NOT be accepted for that week’s album.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][/vc_tab][vc_tab title=\"Other Questions\" tab_id=\"1419783849818-2-0\"][vc_toggle title=\"I have a tech-related problem, like I’m having trouble submitting my photo, or there’s something wrong with the site. Whom do I contact?\" open=\"false\"]Let us know! Send an email to <a href=\"mailto:help@52frames.com\">help@52frames.com</a>, or ask a question on the <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/groups/52fadmin/\" target=\"_blank\">52Frames Photographers’ Facebook group</a>.[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"I want to meet you. Do you have regular meetups “in real life”?\" open=\"false\"]Yes! 52Frames runs monthly “Photowalks” in different cities around the world. Check out our Photowalks page to find out if a photowalk is happening in your area, they are great fun.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"I have a question that’s not on here, whom do I ask?\" open=\"false\"]If you’re not already in our <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/groups/52fadmin/\" target=\"_blank\">52Frames Photographers’ Facebook group</a>, check it out and ask your question there, we’re a very helpful community. You can also email us at <a href=\"mailto:help@52frames.com\">help@52frames.com</a> if you’re having other trouble.\r\n\r\n[/vc_toggle][vc_toggle title=\"How do I sign up for the monthly newsletter?\" open=\"false\"]<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/52frames/app_100265896690345\" target=\"_blank\">Here!</a>[/vc_toggle][/vc_tab][/vc_tour][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Member\'s FAQ','','inherit','open','open','','559-revision-v1','','','2014-12-30 15:37:57','2014-12-30 15:37:57','',559,'http://52frames.com/559-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(564,4,'2014-12-30 15:42:27','2014-12-30 15:42:27','<b>Week 1: Self Portrait</b>\r\n\r\nIt’s become tradition here at 52Frames to start the year with the Self-Portrait challenge. It’s a great way to dive into something quite personal and vulnerable, as well being a great introduction to all the participants (an extreme ice breaker, if you will).\r\n\r\nSelf-portraits are the absolute best way to improve your photography. You have yourself an available model 24/7, a model with endless patience and usually the curious drive to go ahead and try new things. <b>Push yourself to ‘tell your story’, and let yourself be vulnerable to the process; you’ll grow because of it.</b>\r\n\r\nSkills You’ll Learn:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Composition</li>\r\n	<li>Using a Tripod</li>\r\n	<li>Manual Focus</li>\r\n	<li>Remote/Self-timer</li>\r\n	<li>Crafting a Story</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips and Tuts for this week:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>11 Tips for taking great Self Portraits [link and thumbnail]</li>\r\n	<li>[VIDEO] “How to hold your friggin camera”[link and thumbnail]</li>\r\n	<li>Get started right: The best tools for organizing and backing up your photos [link and thumbnail]</li>\r\n	<li>WTF is a megapixel? Your [soon-to-be] complete guide to every photographic term that exists. [link and thumbnail]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Need some inspiration? </b>Check out 25 amazing examples of Self Portrait Photos\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>**Extra Credit Challenge: Tell Your Story</b>\r\n\r\nOne of our ‘3 tenets’ of taking a good photograph: Tell a story. Take a photo with intention. In this case, craft your image to tell ‘your’ story. Perhaps some meaningful objects in the background, or take a photo in your work surroundings. Whatever your story is, make that the intention of the composition, with you being the subject inside that ‘frame.’\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Deadline:</b> January 04, 2015 12:00 Noon EST\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>[SUBMIT YOUR PHOTO BUTTON]</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNeed help with getting started with your camera? Check out our <b>101 Series on Getting to Know Your Camera</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Week 2: Silhouette</b>\r\n\r\nIt’s silhouette week! This great lighting method seems to always be a hit with our community, and it’s a lot of fun to go out and capture.\r\n\r\nNote that silhouette is NOT the same thing as a shadow! Wikipedia defines silhouette as an image represented by a solid shape of a single color, its edging matching the outlines of the subject. In photography terms, it’s when a subject is completely ‘blacked out’ from a brighter light source behind it (16:1 ratio or more.) Apparently the French call this method “Contre-jour,”[ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contre-jour\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contre-jour</a>]  which sounds all fancy, so I think we’ll call it that from now on.\r\n\r\n<b>Tips and Tuts for this week:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>How to photograph a silhouette</li>\r\n	<li>Understanding Light: Back Lighting / Rim light</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Need some inspiration? </b>Check out 25 amazing examples of Silhouette Photos\r\n\r\n<b>**Extra Credit Challenge: Use Artificial Light</b>\r\n\r\nFor those of you with a studio setup, or access to any kind of off-camera lighting, you can set up your scene manually and tell your own unique story, without the use of the sun.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Deadline:</b> January 11, 2015 12:00 Noon EST\r\n\r\n<b>[SUBMIT YOUR PHOTO BUTTON]</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNeed help with getting started with your camera? Check out our <b>101 Series on Getting to Know Your Camera</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Challenges','','publish','open','open','','challenge','','','2014-12-30 15:50:46','2014-12-30 15:50:46','',239,'http://52frames.com/?page_id=564',0,'page','',0),(565,4,'2014-12-30 15:42:27','2014-12-30 15:42:27','<b>Week 1: Self Portrait</b>\r\n\r\nIt’s become tradition here at 52Frames to start the year with the Self-Portrait challenge. It’s a great way to dive into something quite personal and vulnerable, as well being a great introduction to all the participants (an extreme ice breaker, if you will).\r\n\r\nSelf-portraits are the absolute best way to improve your photography. You have yourself an available model 24/7, a model with endless patience and usually the curious drive to go ahead and try new things. <b>Push yourself to ‘tell your story’, and let yourself be vulnerable to the process; you’ll grow because of it.</b>\r\n\r\nSkills You’ll Learn:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Composition</li>\r\n	<li>Using a Tripod</li>\r\n	<li>Manual Focus</li>\r\n	<li>Remote/Self-timer</li>\r\n	<li>Crafting a Story</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips and Tuts for this week:</b>