a href=\"https://secure.flickr.com/photos/haphotography/sets/72157622706626575\">“selfie”</a> project.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_579\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"683\"]<img src=\"http://52frames.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/12-Doreen-Hoerold-Self-Portrait-683x1024.jpg\" alt=\"Doreen Hoerold (Week 1: Self-Portrait - 2014)\" width=\"683\" height=\"1024\" class=\"size-large wp-image-579\" /> Doreen Hoerold (Week 1: Self-Portrait - 2014)[/caption]','Self-Portraits: Tips, Tutorials, and Inspiration','','inherit','open','open','','572-autosave-v1','','','2014-12-30 22:22:27','2014-12-30 22:22:27','',572,'http://52frames.com/blog/uncategorized/572-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(582,4,'2014-12-31 20:29:24','2014-12-31 20:29:24','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.\r\n\r\nBy faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation we\'ve found online, comes from \'Web Video Crew\' in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU?rel=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nOne thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the <strong>intersecting</strong> points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into \'thirds\'. Although this is also a compositional technique with regards to <strong>balance</strong>, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.\r\n\r\nAnother great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the right side of the frame and facing left, as is the truck. The composition is such that there’s “room” for the surfer to surf ‘into’, or the truck to drive ‘into’. Pay mind to where your subject is “looking” and give space in the frame accordingly.\r\n\r\nAs with all our rules we dole out here at 52Frames, understand that many times they are meant to be broken, so don’t worry about getting it exact, just keep this in your \'toolbelt\' and keep it in mind when you shoot.\r\n\r\nNEXT UP: Balance','Rule of Thirds - The Most Important Rule You\'ll Ever Learn. (not really)','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.','inherit','open','open','','351-autosave-v1','','','2014-12-31 20:29:24','2014-12-31 20:29:24','',351,'http://52frames.com/blog/uncategorized/351-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(583,4,'2014-12-30 16:17:13','2014-12-30 16:17:13','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and most basic concept to keep in mind when composing a photo.\r\n\r\nBy faaaar, the most concise and cleanest explanation I\'ve found online, comes from Web Video Crew in this roughly 60 second YouTube video:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/XeKy2SvYpdU?rel=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nOne thing to keep in mind is that the Rule of Thirds refer to the intersecting points on the grid, NOT slicing your composition into 1/3rds. Although this is also a compositional technique, it’s not a part of the Rule of Thirds.\r\n\r\nAnother great point that he mentions in the video is to keep your subject looking “into the frame!” Notice how the surfer is on the right side of the frame and facing left, as is the truck. The composition is such that there’s “room” for the surfer to surf ‘into’, or the truck to drive ‘into’. Pay mind to where your subject is “looking” and give space in the frame accordingly.\r\n\r\nDon’t worry about getting it exact, just keep this in mind as you shoot.\r\n\r\nNEXT UP: Balance','Rule of Thirds - The most important rule you\'ll ever learn. (not really)','Generally the first ‘rule’ taught in photography, the Rule of Thirds is the strongest and m